Hopefully this posts in time - I just watched it today (1/2). Huge recommend to anyone with Saturday (2/2) free to go check out "It's You or Me" at the corpus playroom. Scratch that, cancel your plans.

I've started watching student plays this term (best decision ever) and witnessed so much talent!

It's by far the wittiest and smartest play I've seen this term when it comes to the dialogue. Some jokes took me a while but I caught them just as they were flying over my head. The use of dramaturgy incorporated into the plot is exceptionally clever.

It's a novel concept that's well acted throughout and then the addition of a new character throws the dynamics into haywire. The titular "It's You or Me" emerges at the emotional climax of the play (which was just insane and had me gripped ever since the physical use of that old storytelling device rears its head [go watch to understand this!]).

Then, just as you expect the show to end, there's a late in the day emergence much like Orson Welles in The Third Man, stealing the show from then on.

Thank you to the hard work of the writer, production, and cast for an excellent show!

this is a rave review of week 5 corpus lateshow ‘fallen flowers’, a student-written play about marriage trafficking in china and how the patriarchy feeds young women false ideals of romance and male protection, when what it really does is to dominate and control. the tab has a positive review of this show already, but frankly the cast and crew deserve more than 3.5 stars. no-one even told me to write this. but it has to be said: you were all amazing, well done for putting on this show, big love to you all!! it’s a very long and elaborate production for corpus lateshow, but it really pays off. the scenes (vignettes? sections? stories?), and the monologues, settle into a rhythm. it’s an intense show w intense themes, but somehow the tension still manages to build throughout the show. the costuming, props, and set design were beautiful, lighting and sound were very effective. acting and direction immaculate. special shout-out to whoever runs the instagram - i really liked the informational graphics on there, and the flowers all made sense once i saw the show!! i also really liked the language mixing in the play!! what i really wanted to say though is that this play feels important to exist right now. there have been several high profile cases of marriage trafficking / very bad misogynistic violence in china in recent years, and right now a clamp down on feminist discourse and protests. it gives me hope that we are using our voices to speak out about misogyny, and to remind the world around us that just bc most western countries are free of institutionalised misogynistic violence on this scale, it doesn’t mean this doesn’t occur in other countries to women who are fundamentally no different from us. but anyway - big love to the team behind this amazing production!! if you’ve got this far in my midnight splurge review, pls go see them at corpus playroom feb 24 or 25 (i’m hoping this camfess has come out by then!!)

You can go through king’s as a shortcut during visiting hours (9am to 5pm). The front gate is open but the back one isn’t always open. That’s the way it’s always been, for years (except for when all colleges were closed to non-college members at points in 2020 and 2021). Some colleges don’t let people cut through at all, like Trinity! Surely that’s worse? It would be just as convenient to cut thought Clare, for example, but their back gate is locked. I think the big issue with King's informal style is that they do it in a unique and irreplaceable architectural setting. You walk into the hall, see something truly wondrous, and then feel that the fact it's used as an (admittedly lovely) cafeteria is just incongruous and an immense waste. The low number of formals is something a lot of students who otherwise like Kings regret slightly. I think that if kings wants to be informal that's fine but morally they should build themselves a new, informal, college somewhere else in the city and let a new college that will actually make full use of their incredible site take over. The obvious response to this is "it's our college we can do what we want with it" but Kings was paid for by taxes levied on the entire nation, and is part of our national artistic heritage, turning it into a cafeteria doesn't really work.

Next time, please do your research before getting on Camfess - King’s has one of the highest proportions of state school students out of any college (and one of the highest numbers of state school applicants). It also has one of the best access programmes (the two are likely connected!). Take a look at the state school numbers at John’s and Peterhouse and then get back to me. Honestly, this is such a lazy take. There’s nothing wrong with being from a state school and enjoying gowns and Latin graces, but it has nothing to do with why King’s is non-traditional - it has a reputation for radical political activity that goes back to the 70s. It was also the first college (along with Churchill and Clare) to admit women (in 1972). Generations and generations of students later,  I think many of us at King’s are still proud of our college history, and endeavour to carry on in that spirit. King’s definitely has its issues as a college, but I think it’s not right to ignore that history - it’s more complicated than just not wearing gowns to be different.

It's no coincidence that the colleges with the poshest students (like Kings) insist on rejecting the traditional Cambridge experience - whereas the colleges with the lowest % private school students are the most traditional. Firstly, the students at colleges like Kings or Robinson are self-conscious about their class, and there appears to be some sense that having the traditional experience is flexing your poshness and should be avoided.

so this confession really won't win me any admirers and I know this is the whole point but I kinda wish King's was more like John's or Trinity in some ways (no really). don't get me wrong - we have many of the best fellows in the whole university, seeing the fortress-like front court and chapel every day makes me feel like an actual king lol, we've some of the best views in the city, our main college choir is second to none and puts on the best evensong in all of Cambridge (possibly the world), and the traditionally informal relations between fellows and students allow for some fantastic conversations. but some of you may not also know that kings likes to cultivate a kinda down with the kids, 'alternative' personality and pretend it's not clearly one of the older and grander and more privileged colleges that it is - we don't have proper gowned formals but glorified fancy dress parties each week with different themes; our may ball event ('King's affair'), because of an unfortunate crowd-related disaster some decades ago when we still had a proper grand may ball, has since changed completely so that it's not a black or white tie event at all but a glorified music festival with a different costume theme each year. Idk why our college does this because the traditional cambridge experience is so fun on its own, and our dining hall is indisputably one of the best in all of Cambridge, and yet for some reason (I think the student body largely) the college feels like it's punching below its weight sometimes in what it could be giving in the way of a traditional cambridge experience. i wouldn't change my college for the world, the reputation of kings, its music, its academics and its architecture are all a massive ego boost for a start. but idk, I feel like it could also really milk the cambridge experience more (maybe the reason it doesn't do so is because unlike other colleges it has nothing to prove - ours is the most famous college here, after all).

The day after graduation, I decided to show King’s College to my parents. I had plenty of supervisions there, so I completely forgot that, as tourists, we were not supposed to get past those little gates, even though it said “No Entry” on them. While I was walking with my parents, one of the workers (not the gatekeepers nor the porters – they were all sooo kind) told us that we weren’t supposed to be there. I immediately apologised – it was an honest mistake (I wasn’t trying to be sneaky or anything). But he was so rude about it and made us walk the long way back, around the college’s back and then along the chapel (although we were literally next to the college’s entrance, ready to leave). What doesn’t sit well with me was the way he spoke to us – I kept apologising (and meant it), but all he could say was, “The sign’s pretty big”. It was quite humiliating to be told off like that in front of my parents, and it was also something I did not need at all before leaving Cambridge for good. King’s always finds a way to ruin it for the rest of us.

Not sure if this has been said yet in the Kings night walk-through debate, but I think a big chunk of the internal college decision making was because a lot of the staircases don’t lock. I know that a member of Kings isn’t inherently safer than anyone else, but you can maybe see how letting in more people to college (including strangers) who are then able to access students’ kitchens, bathrooms, and sometimes even bedrooms, would be detrimental to the safety of their own students. I know for a fact that during the day, tourists wandering behind the allowed area signs have ended up in students kitchens, or even bedrooms. I am aware and sympathetic that being able to walk through would potentially make a safer environment for people walking home at night, but hopefully you can also understand that in the first instance, a college’s priority will always be its own students?

Why does Kings let tourists in but not students? I'm not here to justify just explaining what I was told by the Domus Bursar at King's. The chapel costs just under £20 million a year to keep heated. This is done through floor heating but is dated and inefficient. They can make at least £10 million a year through tourists, which subsidies the heating of the chapel. They want to replace the underfloor heating and fix the shit lead roof, but this will be very time-consuming, so have not pulled the trigger. When they do, the chapel will be out of use for a while. They are also talking about solar panels at the top. I'm not JUSTIFYING just recalling what I've been told! Fun fact: You can get a tour round the top of the chapel as a King's student. You can take non-king students just ask the Domus Bursar.

1. Kings lets in so many tourists, so any arguments about a "warm, insulated-from-the wider-world quality" that you're being forced to surrender aren't really relevant - the college has already willingly surrendered this for money, why not extend it to other colleges' students as well at this point 2. Kings is far harder to get into than Trinity or Johns, where 4 times out of 5 you can just walk straight in through the plodge (** there's definitely white privilege here, but that's a whole other issue **). Kings you have to justify your presence, show your camcard and jump through all these arbitrary hoops. It is a problem with all the river colleges to varying degrees, but Kings is by far one of the least accessible. 3. Kings' location makes it way more desirable to cut through - the nearest public bridges are both 5+ minutes walk away, so if you're trying to get back to Caius accommodation/Robinsons/Clare Hall/Selwyn/Newnham etc at night, it's a lot quicker and safer to go through Kings 4. That said, it's not just an issue with Kings - other colleges need to be less gatekeepy as well

Can I just say to all the people who complain that they don't get unrestricted access to King's, we won't give it up unless all colleges offer the same kind of access. I hate that other colleges that are just  as famous and iconic like Trinity and John's get to routinely prevent randomers from entering their premises and no one bats an eye, but when King's does it everyone goes insane. If we're going to let everyone through (which I'm not even opposed to in principle), get the other stuffy colleges to do so too, because it's not fair that other colleges get to preserve that warm, insulated-from-the-wider-world quality and we should have to surrender it.

I really enjoyed Newnham Garden Party on the whole and thought it was well-planned overall with good music, drinks, and atmosphere, but my experience was somewhat soured by seeing the owls that were tethered in an area on one of the lawns. One of them was tethered directly in the bright sun, which was so blazing this afternoon that I had to look for shade after 30 minutes in it started to make me feel faint. I can't imagine how that would affect the sensitive eyes of a creature adapted to live in the darkness. The owls were also all surrounded by students, who did their best to be respectful as far as I saw but did get quite close to get photos sometimes and were naturally having fun (as they should be!) so were sometimes a bit tipsy and having loud conversations, not to mention the noise from the main band across the garden. One of the birds looked visibly distressed at points, but the keeper was busy with a queue of students waiting to take photos with the owls on their arms and didn't check on the tethered birds once that I could see in the 30 minutes I was there. I don't think it's anyone's fault who attended the event, who wouldn't have intended any harm, but owls are nocturnal creatures that prefer quiet environments and a loud, sunny, garden party seems like it would naturally make them stressed and unhappy.

Overheard/seen with my very own ears and eyes, around 8:36pm, Sidge Ave: Amid the dense and silent cold, there comes a voice approaching from the opposite side of the road, intoning in a rhythmic mezzo forte: "fuck-you new-nham" *Three lads on bikes appear, single file, loosely spaced* One of the lads: "Why aren't you repeating after me? It's meant to be a chant!" First lad: fuck-you-new-nham! Others: Fuck you Newnham! First lad: fuck-you-new-nham! Others: Fuck you Newnham! *and so on, riding off into the distance* They thought nobody saw them. They thought nobody cared. But I did. And as the petty person I am, I'm writing a whole camfess about it. From those few seconds, I have no way of knowing what might have provoked such a bizarre event. But let's just say that at first, I kinda assumed that the existence of all-female colleges at Cambridge was mostly some sort of quirk/relic of history, though of course some people might prefer a single-sex college for personal or religious reasons. (all the old prestigious schools in my home country are single sex as well because they were founded way back when). After this, I realise that this is the sort of thing that explains why places like Newnham still need to exist. Smh.

The real tea about the Newnham party room is that it was built by Margret Thatcher in the Cold War as a nuclear bunker. (This is why it is entirely painted blue, because Thatcher believed that the colour of the Conservative Party was much better and minimising the effects of nuclear weapons.) however, once Diane Abbott (newnham alumn) became the first black female MP with Labour, the college became embarrassed about their tory past and made the room into storage space to hide its Thatcherite origins. That is the REAL reason that it isn’t used.

As an ancient 4th year the tea I heard about the Newnham party room/bar from my college mum was that it was only ever designed to be a storage room in the first place. A proper bar and bop space was promised when they knocked down the old building, but one of the staff members at the time who was in charge of food and drink was opposed to alcohol on religious grounds and so instead of the Iris space being a combined cafe/bar like in other colleges any bar or alcohol related materials had to be kept in the locked cupboard it's currently in, and whereas the cafe was run by catering staff the bar was run by student "volunteers" who were initially paid in £5 vouchers. When they opened the new conference centre they stuck "Party Room" on a basement storage room and painted the walls, floor and ceiling bright blue so that they could claim they'd kept their promise. I went to a JCR event there in my first year which was pretty crap as the space isn't designed to be used as a party room. It's really small, you can't have glasses as the floor is concrete and anything dropped smashes, and the combination of no windows and entirely blue surfaces made you feel like you were floating in some kind of sweaty smurf hell.

As a fellow Christ’s student, I have to agree with this. Obviously it’s wonderful to celebrate when people achieve highly, but in a college where around half of students achieve firsts things like scholars’ dinner start to feel more about who’s excluded than who’s included. It would be very easy for the college to give out a small reward - eg an ornament or a book voucher - without making such a huge deal about it. There are so many scholars, and so many things in which scholars are included, that it can start to feel like there are two tiers of student, and more like you’re being punished for not getting a first than like others are being celebrated for getting one.

Christ’s might have topped Tompkin’s Table again but the stereotype about Christ’s being incredibly academically competitive is painfully true, at least in my experience. I just finished my first year at Christ’s and I’m appalled by how intense and unhealthy the environment is here and more than anything how DoS and supervisors feed and facilitate this pressure. The other students here are great people, but it’s clear that the precedent set by our supervisors and DoS makes students here very competitive (not in an intentionally malicious way but people certainly compare hours spent studying every day, their results and rank much more than my friends from other colleges). I’m dreading the beginning of next year because I know that everyone will know who didn’t get a first after the scholar’s dinner and I’m embarrassed that I didn’t get one (even though a 2.i is still a great result that I would have been proud of if the standard wasn’t that everything else than a first is subpar). Things like having designated scholar’s rooms, only scholars getting to say grace at formals and the scholar’s ceremony/dinner all create a very public and obvious divide between being “good enough” and “not deserving” and it’s hard to be on the latter side of that line when your worth and results have been so closely tied by college. I love my friends here but being at Christ’s is really taking its toll on my mental health and I wish the college would consider revoking some of these practices.

Why is St John’s Voices really being shut down? It is a very successful choir and provides opportunities for female singers of all vocal types, while the main college choir does not include sopranos, limiting opportunities for women. Indeed, there is currently only one female singer in St John’s College Choir. The statement put out by John’s regarding music in the college (https://www.joh.cam.ac.uk/music-college-st-johns-statement) implies SJV is sucking up resources which could instead be used for more accessible music opportunities including ‘masterclasses in music, for example on song writing’ and supporting ‘new opportunities for non-auditioned singing’. The implication seems to be that SJV is somehow elitist. Additionally, the statement claims ‘Students’ preferences and experiences in music today are different from those of previous generations, and many of them have had fewer musical opportunities in school than might have been the case in the past.’ This implies SJV essentially is being scrapped because state schools are failing to provide music opportunities and training to pupils. This is pretty sad and illogical if true. Additionally, the college stresses in the statement the ‘significant resources currently devoted to St John’s Voices’, but I wonder how much the choir really costs to run. The whole move to scrap SJV seems rather underhanded and I don’t see why a high-level choir like SJV cannot coexist with more accessible music opportunities, especially in a college as rich as St John’s. By the way, I am not a member of SJV, I am just confused about why the choir apparently needs to be scrapped. Here is a link to the petition to save SJV: https://www.change.org/p/save-st-john-s-voices-stop-cutting-opportunities-for-female-singers-in-cambridge

TLDR: John's ball committee and the musicians are both handling things terribly. As a musician who has played at every major may ball (including John's) in my years here, I wonder whether people fully appreciate how absurd the situation with John's is. The deposit system was ridiculous: I understand that it is standard for events, but it is stupid to treat student bands like professional ones. We are not paid anything near what a professional band would be, so expecting us (broke students) to be able to cough up deposit money like real adults could, especially when most of us don't see much or any profit from playing, is not at all feasible. I think this was a case of John's being so desperate to make the ball as "professional" as possible that they neglected the realities of working within a student context. That said, I think that the musicians' response has been incredibly childish too. There was some good work done early on with helping musicians communicate with each other about the deposit and how to combat the practice, but since then the group has devolved into name-calling and heel-dragging. Instead of focusing on how to help musicians like at the start, since all the boycott announcements the focus has moved into the completely unproductive front of trying to slander John's on social media. Entire days were spent whining about John's removing tags on Instagram instead of actually working towards anything (and, as #Camfession36094 noted, having the gall to compare this minor problem with the fucking Chinese government) and the one person who actually managed to forge a genuinely insightful dialogue with some of the John's committee members did so on his own, only for the musicians to start quibbling with him on the chat rather than, for example, taking what he's said into account and writing a new letter to John's. This isn't my fight; I'm not playing this year and have been focusing on my thesis over playing music all year, but the idiotic and childish way this has been conducted on both sides annoys the hell out of me.

I was initially extremely excited to be performing at Johns’ May Ball - it was a fantastic opportunity to be looking forward to post-exams. Now, I’m just extremely annoyed and honestly eaten up with more stress that I simply didn’t need during exam season. For those who don’t know, Johns’ has decided to charge deposits for all of their student performers. This was initially at a whopping £260 per individual in the band and also only targeted to smaller, newer bands. After an obvious outcry from student performers about the ridiculousness and frank unfairness of this, they quickly backtracked and said they would reduce this to £50 per person for all groups. This is still way more than what I’m getting paid for my performance as a whole. I’m honestly kind of dumbfounded. As a student with loans on my head, I’m now expected to be paying the May Ball ahead of my performance for the glory of being able to be there. Their justification for this is that big festivals like Latitude and so on have this system so that their bands actually turn up or so that bands don’t gatecrash the event afterwards. Please can I point out that no other Cambridge May Ball does this? Why does Johns’ think it is so much better than everyone else that it needs to enforce such a system on students? Rather than looking forward to the event I’m now just stressed. I want to make sure I can turn up, play my piece and disappear quickly so that they have no excuses to claim my money. God forbid I get ill on the day - I’ll have to hope that they don’t use my illness and inability to perform to leave me significantly poorer than before. If you’re feeling just as angry after reading this, then please do interact with this post - we need all the support we can get in order to put more pressure on them to abolish the deposit system :/

I am so proud of the John’s community tonight. During the second grace at hall, all the (pissdrunk) students engaged in their regular game of “how much can I make my chair squeak”, an innocent and time-honoured tradition. But the head caterer (?) was clearly in a bad mood because he snarled “well I’m not going to start until you stop playing with your chairs”. Of course this made us giddy, but we stopped anyway, in desperation for our desserts. But predictably, as soon as the first Latin syllable was uttered, there went the chairs again! So our old friend stopped the reading: “I’m going to stop there and we can all stand in silence for two minutes”. Let me tell you, I was fighting for my LIFE trying not to explode in laughter, and I’m certain everyone else in the room felt the same, grinning like idiots at the surreal situation of us all being disciplined like schoolboys. Even the fellows looked a bit pissed off that they were being made to wait - I mean they have busy lives to get on with! Clearly the grouchy caterer realised his mistake and resumed the grace after about 40 seconds (poor show - at least commit to it). And of course, when the reading was finished, everyone sat down and exploded into laughter. Brilliant. (Hope the guy’s okay tho cuz he got done dirty by the entire hall)

I hope all the other May Balls don’t follow suit and reveal they’re only going to serve vegan food like Darwin. Having paid over £100 to attend a May Ball this year, I’ll be really disappointed if it turns out the food isn’t going to be what I expected (and, quite frankly, what I paid for). Yes, vegan food can also be good, but the options are by definition less varied than for non-vegan options. I also think that in general this desire to make everything vegan has gone too far. People’s diet is a personal decision and people shouldn’t be patronised by having their dietary choices made for them, especially when the majority of the student body is still meat eating. On top of that, as has already been pointed out, serving only vegan options excludes people with certain dietary requirements. Darwin’s May Ball committee have said that they will “cater to as many dietary requirements as possible”, but what will they say to people who have been told by doctors they are medically unable to go vegan, as well as the circumstances already mentioned in previous Camfesses? Try as you might, only serving vegan food is always going to be less inclusive than serving a variety of foods, because the variety of base options is lower. Bearing in mind that the food served at a May Ball can only ever be a drop in the environmental pond, May Balls should focus on other options for cutting or offsetting their carbon footprint which will not result in the exclusion of some students in the process. Also, quite frankly, I’ll be pretty frustrated if I only find out after having paid for a May Ball that the food isn’t going to be anything like what I’d expected.

Fitz admit on their website that they did initially refuse booking, but then changed their mind after being approached by legal representatives. Hereafter, Christian Concern declined an offer for dates different to those originally requested.

Alright sorry to be the guy but Fitz being heralded as this beacon of the LGBT inclusivity because of the Christian Concern lawsuit is chat and it’s time to explain why. For those who don’t know, Fitzwilliam College is being sued by Christian Concern because the latter tried to hold a conference at Fitz and Fitz said no. Christian Concern have decided that Fitz did so due to political disagreement with Christian Concern’s values, and are suing them for infringing their right to free speech or some shit. Most people have taken Christian Concern’s reasoning and used it to shower Fitz in praise and medals, but that’s not why Fitz rejected them. We don’t know for sure why Fitz said no to Christian Concern’s desired dates, but as graduation later fell on those dates it’s likely those plans were being finalised when Christian Concern got in touch for the conference, and Fitz wanted to keep the dates free. We know that Fitz were otherwise happy to host Christian Concern, as Fitz OFFERED OTHER DATES to Christian Concern. Fitz never rejected them in the first place; they just rejected those dates. Christian Concern is just suing them because that’s the primary thing they do — attack Muslims and queer people, and fund the legal costs of affiliated Christians who are in court for doing the same in order to stay in the headlines. Fitz isn’t a good place to be LGBT. There are some absolutely lovely Christians at Fitz, who love everybody and demand a lot of respect. These Christians disassociate with the Fitz Christian Soc, because that Soc has been publicly homo, trans, bi, and islamophobic for I don’t even know how long, but I was warned about it by my college parents upon arrival and it’s still true now. This presence has been told to college and no action has been taken. Instead, when reported to the porters by one of this group, college porters force queer students to take down their pride flags, while permitting other types of flags to be proudly displayed. Frankly, this is likely why Christian Concern chose Fitz for their conference, as most colleges don’t have a Christian Soc with both the values and longevity of Fitz’. For balance, the Fitz Chaplain is wonderful and open to everybody, and the college bar is legitimately a queer safe space. If any attacks happened in the bar, it would be taken seriously. And part of the issues around being queer at Fitz are with particular problem queers within the student body who make queer socials at the college inaccessible, it’s not all to do with the Christian Soc, as harmful as that group of Christians is. Anyway the reason why I’m writing this is just to get the facts out there. The Christian Concern thing has been brought up multiple times to me since I got here, from people who saw the original misinformation post on Camfess about how great Fitz is for standing its ground (which never happened). So hopefully the people who read that post will read this one and realise it’s just Christian Concern outright making things up — which is Fitz’ legal defence, if you look into it. Fitz doesn’t think twice about queer rights, but this case has made them paranoid about criticism from Christians, and all of their statements are written to Christians if you read them carefully. That really says it all. P.S. I am queer and I’m not Muslim so I’ve tried not to talk on behalf of Muslims here, but the way Muslims have been completely ignored by people following this story is sad and shows how much work needs to be done in that area. Christian Concern grew its platform because it was the main anti-Muslim Christian group — so many others out there were anti-queer it was practically mainstream — and yet when Christian Concern does something like this everyone only thinks about the queer community. That ain’t right.

Yes we are smaller and yes we have lesser financial support, and this may not be suitable for everyone understandly, but often times with a small college comes a big heart. Words cannot express how loved and supported I've felt at this college. The college community is also so wonderful, you don't have to be the closest friends with everyone to just sit there and have a chat. Please could people at Lucy Cav be more mindful when chatting about disability exemptions for room balloting. It’s understandable that people feel the system had been taken advantage of, and that it is unfair so many desirable rooms have been taken, but I think some lines have been crossed. As someone with a diagnosed disability that affects my day-to-day life, I was relieved to get an exemption this year - regardless of whether I could live with a friend. I’ve heard people complain that, because there are less rooms available, their large friend groups will be split up. I was entirely willing to not live with my friends if it meant my access needs were met so as I could live with less pain and exhaustion. But I now feel incredible guilt whenever I hear people talking about the room ballot. People have asked me if I have a “real disability”, or if I’m “actually disabled though”, or not to “rub it in”. Without question, I would gladly swap my new build room for a normal 20-year-old body in an instant. I would give so much more than the cost of new build rent to have a normal student experience instead of feeling stuck in the body of an 80-year-old. Please remember that. I already had to prove to the University DRC that I am medically disabled, which the college then have to evaluate, too, so, while I appreciate your frustration, I really don’t need the judgement.

The Tab’s coverage of Pembroke May Ball is genuinely embarrassing. It’s such a cheap and unscrupulous move that puts them on the same level as the very worst of this country’s media. If you want people to take your organisation even a little bit seriously, don’t produce almost identical content to the Daily Mail. The headlines and framing of the articles are misleading and it’s glaringly obvious to anyone with any common sense. Of course the theme couldn’t be changed the day before an event where hundreds of thousands of pounds were spent to cater to an incredibly specific theme. Of course there was no malice or even intention behind the deeply ironic coincidence, because it was just that: a coincidence. It is so disappointing to see student journalism at this uni of such low quality, and which so obviously prioritises engagement over truth or accurate representation. I know it’s just student journalism, but there should at least be some moral standards behind their journalistic choices, and right now I’m embarrassed to have this kind of reporting associated with my university.

What does varsity think it is really achieving by spinning the Pem May ball theme as some kind of act of disrespect? Any reasonably-minded person accepts literally nothing could have been done given the circumstances and allowing the national press to vilify the committee in the way that they have is just plain disgusting. Short of cancelling the May Ball outright there and then (which no-one in the college would have supported), they did the only decent, possible thing they could have done- express regret. I honestly don’t know why some individuals have sought to promote this story and take it out of context (including asking the family for comment), but all I can say is they probably ought to consider their social responsibility.

I applied to Selwyn after visiting it and Selwyn being constantly gassed up by my friend. The same day I got my offer from the college my friend began saying stuff like: 'Ah damn you should have applied to a city centre college like Kings or Trinity and put Selwyn as your second choice' 'Selwyn is a bit dead compared to the bigger colleges' 'Selwyn not that good' So I went home that day and started googling Selwyn and getting annoyed that I didn't pick the 'right college'. Was pretty annoyed and even started reading about the other colleges I 'should have' applied to. That night I had a dream that I went on a spiritual and lifelong mission to find why Selwyn was the right college for me. The dream involved car chases, having to get past aggressors stopping me getting on flights as part of my 'journey to find the meaning of Selwyn', me climbing mountains and even going on different train journeys across the world on a conquest to discover why Selwyn is the greatest college. I failed my mission and did not find the Selwyn meaning of life. I went home disappointed (still in my dream). Things changed however, when I went into my office and sadly reached for my birth certificate. I had given up all hope. A mini-rant on 3 years of Sidney Sussex Accommodation: - Numerous pretty fundamental infrastructural issues (widely inconsistent shower hot water and pressure in certain staircases, a lift that is working on a coin flip on any given day, entries and exists into college breaking and being fixed every other week it seems, and others) - A ~12% increase in rent for next year - No compromises on students using their own appliances for food, despite woeful kitchen distribution in accomodation, and college-provided appliances being very unreliable (a college kettle has failed a college PAT-test, I've been told) - Being kicked out 10am the day after graduation (I hear this is normal for Cambridge, but given everything else it does feel like a gut punch) - Not to mention the Varsity article earlier this year on the numerous accessibility issues the college has seemingly completely ignored until the article was published (funny that) I love my friends here and I have made some great memories, but honestly all of this will leave a bad taste in my mouth as I graduate this week.

In the unlikely event that anyone has any college envy of Trinity, may I present to you the scandal which I am calling Shitgate: Some weeks ago a group of Trinity rowers gathered together in the evening. The cursed events that followed have deeply disturbed those of us who have since heard of them. As the evening progressed and the rowers presumably got increasingly drunk, a game of ‘gay chicken’ began. This culminated in what a previous Camfess termed a “Trinity bisexual poop orgy”. ‘Where does “poop” enter the matter?’ you may ask. Well. As their game progressed, the rowers proceeded to wank each other off on the roof of Neville’s Court (right above where the library skylights are, as I understand it). While it may be disagreeable behaviour, this does in all fairness constitute a good performance at gay chicken. Poo then enters the story when the rowers re-entered the staircase. Not content with public masturbation atop a historic 17th century building, one rower then decided (through some utterly incomprehensible thought process) to commit an unthinkable and morally criminal act. He took a shit on somebody’s windowsill. After the occupant of the room then discovered the poo (which a source tells me the occupant initially believed to be “a stick”), the rower returned to clean up his literal shit. But personally, I don’t think this makes the crime of the poo any better - it was an inexcusable and filthy act of barbarity. This incident has for weeks been covered up by the mysterious workings of Trinity’s boat club. In fact, multiple of the deviants who participated in the events of the Shitgate story are, or have been, senior members of the boat club committee. But now, following my investigative endeavours, I present my evidence to Camfess in the hope of bringing to light the depravity of some members of the First and Third Trinity Boat Club. I can only hope that by sharing this information, which I believe to be firmly in the public interest, some rowers will come to realise the need to stop and think about their actions, and stop plaguing Trinity with their behaviour. I can only assume that any poor soul who has read this far is as bewildered and revolted at Shitgate as those of us doomed to inhabit Trinity have been. We can only live in the hope that the cursed hellscape of moral corruption and vileness that is Trinity College will one day change for the better.

Was walking around Gamla Stan in Stockholm when we saw a poster advertising the Caius choir concert on July 5. Decided to be an encouraging uni member and support the choir by going to the concert. Unfortunately got to the cathedral (concert location) about 2-3 minutes late and so went up to open the big cathedral doors (planned to slip in the back) where multiple signs for the concert were displayed. Lady probably working for the cathedral opened the door saying the cathedral was closed for a concert and we needed tickets (I’m unsure if this was tickets for entering the cathedral or for the concert cause we usually just buy tickets within the chapel for cam concerts) and that we should come back the following morning at 9. I don’t know if I was socially profiled as a tourist and they decided I was not there for the concert, and unfortunately they locked the doors in my face before I could explain I was there for the concert and not the cathedral. At that moment I was quite shocked, but then in the following 20-30 minutes I watched the fiasco of another 10 or so people trying to open the doors to watch the concert as well. Interestingly, there were three people who persevered, 2 of who managed to be let in by the cathedral staff unlocking the large doors - probably because they had digital tickets. Sadly the third person who appeared connected to the choir in some way was not allowed in, perhaps because they didn’t have a ticket? They had appeared to have made a call to someone which had resulted in the cathedral staff unlocking the large doors for them, but they weren’t allowed in because they didn’t have a digital ticket. I hope the concert went well and perhaps they locked the doors early because they were recording the concert or something similar, but I have a few questions about this that I would like to ask: 1. Is it common practice to lock the doors three minutes after the stated start time? 2. The posters that were advertised around the cathedral didn’t say anything about prebooking tickets, was there a place detailing this? 3. What was going on?
